diff:1619417297:1619417297:=1,40d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Expansion: Some personal experience%0a%3c :Author: xiranw%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.DiscriminationAgainstMandarinSpeakers|DiscriminationAgainstMandarinSpeakers]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.khushiw|khushiw]]%0a%3c :Section: B%0a%3c :Completed: 25.04.2021 - 23:08%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c This is certainly not pleasant to talk about, but I can attest to this as it happened to my family when we visited Hong Kong almost 10 years ago. I only vaguely remember the visit (and I’m almost glad I don’t remember much, as it would likely just make me more outraged), but my parents say that we were ignored a few times when requesting service (checking in at a hotel, ordering at a restaurant, etc.) in Mandarin. Only after my parents switched to using English did we finally get serviced. %0a%3c %0a%3c I also remember one time in high school when I was talking to a friend who had just returned from a visit to Hong Kong to see family. She said that her family would always use Cantonese or English in public places because Mandarin speakers tended to be refused service. This discussion was actually what prompted me to ask my parents about our visit to Hong Kong, and I discovered that unfortunately, what my friend said was true.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
